fields.physical_description:
[Grass (Large)] A thick beige rectangle of card. The card is plain on one side, but green on the other. It has been sprayed with flecks of fabric to achieve an even covering. 
[Grass (Small)] A thick beige rectangle of card. The card is plain on one side, but green on the other. It has been sprayed with flecks of fabric to achieve an even covering. 
[Fence] Moulded plastic fence pieces, each with lattice work at the top of the fence, and what looks like weaved wood for the majority of the rest. The fence pieces are a variety of dark browns, and there is a wood effect moulded into the plastic to add realism.
[Ground Piece (Small)] Moulded plastic piece of ground, coloured with dark and light brown. It is raised in places, and has nine holes drilled into the plastic to place trees and shrubbery.
[Ground Piece (Large)] Largely rectangular moulded plastic piece of ground, coloured with dark and light brown. It has been moulded to produce two levels of ground. 22 holes have been drilled into the plastic so that trees and other shrubbery can be positioned in there
[Ground Rectangle] Rectangular moulded plastic in dark brown with around 22 holes drilled into each one so that trees and shrubbery can be added. The top of each rectangle has been moulded to create a relief effect.
[Long Ground Rectangle] Long rectangle of moulded plastic with a straight line of nine drilled holes. The plastic has been moulded to give it a weathered look.
[Ground Quadrants] Moulded plastic quadrants in brown plastic. Each have around 10 holes drilled into it and have a mottled effect.
[Short Ground Rectangle] Short moulded plastic rectangles with 5 holes of varying sizes on each one. The plastic is a mix of dark green and dark brown.
[Pillar] Moulded pale brown plastic with moulded brick effect pillar. A hole has been drilled at both ends.
[Pillar Square] Pale cream squares suitable for the tops of the pillars. On one side is a small hole drilled, so that plants and other adornments can be placed on top. The other side has a larger hole, suitable for fixing the square to the pillar.
[Cold Frame] Moulded green plastic in a square/rectangle shape, some indentations moulded into the outside to give it a wood-effect.
[Cold Frame Lid] White moulded plastic lid with two bars for a cold frame. 
[Crazy Paving] Rectangles of thick card with printed paper stuck to one side. The paper is printed with 'crazy paving' slabs
[Stone Wall] Moulded plastic stone wall of a variety of colours, mainly creams and browns. The plastic has been moulded to give a brick effect, and the top of the wall has five holes, so that plants could be added.
[Tree Base] Moulded plastic bases for trees, mainly in greens and browns. Each has a hole in it for placing a tree.
[Rocks] Moulded plastic rocks in grey and white. Each has a small protrusion on the base so that it can fixed to the ground
[Shed Back Wall] Brown moulded plastic with horizontal lines across it. 
[Shed Side Wall] Moulded plastic with horizontal lines moulded into it. It has one edge at a diagonal to the otherwise rectangle design.
[Shed Front Wall] Moulded plastic with horizontal stripes. Designed to cover half the front wall.
[Shed Bench] Dark green moulded plastic with horizontal lines running the length of the bench. 
[Shed Roof] White moulded plastic windows without glass or perspex
[Shed Hooks] Moulded green plastic rectangle, with some moulded lines on the top.
[Greenhouse Side Wall] Dark green moulded plastic rod with ten hooks moulded onto it
[Greenhouse End Wall] White moulded plastic walls with 11 windows on each
[Greenhouse Roof] Moulded white plastic. The walls have a point at the top, giving them five sides, rather than the traditional four. 
[Greenhouse Bench] White moulded plastic with 14 window panels without perspex or glass
[Roof Supports] White moulded plastic benches. Four pieces of plastic made to look like wooden slats
[Well] Moulded white plastic roof supports in triangle shapes
[Rock Pool Rocks] Moulded plastic well in pale brown plastic. It has been painted in some parts with a vivid green paint.
[Rock Pool Water] Grey and white rocks moulded together to form a clear border for a pond
[Rock Pool Water (Card)] Perspex sheet with curved edges designed to act as water in a pool. 
[Flower Pot] Printed card with dark green and yellow ripple effects to give the impression of water in the pond.
[Gardener] Small plastic red flower pots on grey plastic bases. 
[Wheelbarrow] Plastic male gardener on a small mount, wearing blue trousers and a yellow shirt. He is posed as if using a digging tool (which are listed separately). The paint is flaking slightly on the figure.
[Planting Tools] Green plastic wheelbarrow frame with red wheels with black towers and a detachable silver barrow
[Tap] Moulded plastic in bold colours in the shape of spade handles. The other end is a metal prong.
[Bright Green Leaves] Moulded red plastic tap
[Burgundy Leaves] Clusters of plastic leaves fanning out from a central point
[Mottled Leaves] Clusters of burgundy leaves fanning out from a central point
[Thin Leaves] Clusters of mottled green and burgundy leaves fanning out from a central point
[Lupins] Clusters of thin green leaves fanning out around a central point
[Miscellaneous Flowers] Stalks of lupin flowers of various colours. All have leaves down the bottom half of the stalks
[Sprouts] An assortment of miscellaneous individual flowers for attaching to the flower beds. 
[Small Sprouts] Moulded green plastic sprouts. Each has around 6 straight plastic shoots coming from a central point
[Ivy] Green plastic sprouts. Each one has around 8 fluffy shoots coming from a central point
[Leaf Stems] Each green sprout fans out from a central point, some with ivy leaves, while other are bigger and plain. Made from plastic
[Long Sprouts] Long stems with green plastic leaves placed at equal intervals along the stalk
[Flat Sprouts] Moulded green flowers, each with layers of leaves
[Gorse Sprouts] Plastic sprouts in the shape of water reeds in dark green plastic
[Small Branches] Moulded plastic sprouts, consisting of three or four individual stalks coming from a small bulb at one end
[Bare Trees] Sprouts of plastic in dark green with thin paler green leaves across all of the stems. All stems fan out from a central point. 
[Small Trees] Moulded plastic bare brances in a mixture of pale green and pale brown plastic. The colours have been merged slightly to create a patterned effect. Each branch has a number of small branches coming away from the central piece.
[Sprigs] Plastic bare trees in a variety of dark green, dark brown and dark grey colours. Two of the trees are tall and thin, while a third is more weathered, wider and shorter.
[Water Reeds] Miniature trees with dark green trunks and matching colour leaves. The trees are completely flat.
[Brown Gorse Trees] Green plastic sprigs with a variety of leaves of different plant species. They are of varying heights.
[Shrubs] Two long stems of green plastic coming from a central bulb in different directions, forming the shape of water reeds
[Miscellaneous Small Plant Details] Dark brown flat gorse trees without flowers
[Leaves] Shrubs with leaves and stems in the same colour dark green
[Bushes] Small miscellaneous leaves, flowers and sprigs, all in mint green. 
[Bricks] Green leaves made of plastic
[Gates] Small green bush-shaped plastic models, all have been moulded to look like they consist of many leaves
[Seed Beds] Individual plastic brick structures, in beige, red and brown plastic
[Pergola Pieces] Thin black plastic gates with curled adornments
[Garden Bench] Brown plastic seed beds, with three separate lines for planting seeds and small plants and flowers
[Garden Chairs] Brown and green plastic panels, made to look like interlocking pieces of tree branch
[Lawnmower] White plastic bench
[Roller] White plastic chairs
[Hose Pipe] The frame and basket of the lawnmower are a green plastic, with some red detailing around the engine. The engine, mechanism and blades are all in a dark grey metal.
[Rake] Thin green plastic handle for a roller, with a hollow beige plastic cylinder attached to it. When untouched, the handle of the roller sits upright
[Hoe] Thin green plastic frame for the hose pipe with thin orange hollow wire in place of a hose
[Pitchfork] Brown plastic rake with eight teeth at the base
[Shrubbery] Brown plastic handle and silver plastic blade
[Collie Dog] Brown plastic handle and painted silver prongs
[German Shepherd] Dark green stems with mint green leaves that are detachable
[Cat (Standing)] Plastic collie dog painted with orange and white patches
[Cat (Sitting)] Moulded plastic german shepherd with painted red mouth
[Seat] Black moulded plastic with painted details, such as a patch of white under the chin and on each of the paws
[Canopy] Sitting black cat with painted white chin, tail and paws
[Top Beam] Pale blue moulded plastic with a significant fold in the plastic to make it into a seat. It looks like six cushions, with detailing moulded into them
[Arm] Printed card canopy with three lines of perforation to easily fold the canopy to fit the frame. It has a hole in each corner, and has red and white stripes across it.
[Canopy Support] White moulded plastic beam
[Canopy Support Triangle] White plastic arms for the garden couch
[Sprinkler] White moulded plastic triangles, acting as support beams

fields.public_access_description: This floral garden was made by Britains Ltd. in the early 1960s in England. The idea behind the garden was that an initial set or pieces could be bought, with expansion packs and extra items available to improve and diversify the garden. The pieces fit together with ease, and can be easily split up and put back together again. What this achieves is a level of variety and change that ensures children don't get bored of playing.
fields.history_note:
As remembered by the donor Susan North (Curator of 17th & 18th Century Fashion, V&A) -
We lived in Britain for three years in the 1960s, from September 1963 to July 1966.  My father served in the Canadian Army and he had a posting in London during this time.  We lived in Kenley – south of Croydon.  I was seven years old when we arrived in 1963.   I can’t quite remember first encountering the floral garden sets – it must have been in the Purley toy shop.  My brother was very keen on all the Britains miniature soldiers and I was enchanted with the floral garden.  I had never seen anything like it – I don’t think Britains distributed in North America.   My parents must have bought me the first pieces – probably one or two of the flower beds.  I saved my pocket money to buy various sets and it was always high on my Christmas list.  Eventually  the  Britains ‘lawns’ proved inadequate for all the flower beds, so my father found a large piece of plywood and painted it green for me to set everything up on it (alas, it didn’t fit in a shoe box and so didn’t survive).  

I spent countless hours arranging and rearranging the rock garden, the frog pond, the garden shed and the rose trellis.  Half the fun was putting it all together, ’planting’ the flowers, putting all the rosebuds on the bushes.  When directed to tidy up and put it away, I always complied as it meant experiencing the fun of getting it all set up again.   Remarkably, it’s almost all complete (might have lost a tulip or hyacinth blossom along the way), but not because of any influence from my parents.  I was quite particular about keeping it all together and hated the thought of anything being missing (a curator in the making!).

There was no question of leaving it behind when we returned to Canada in 1966 and through my teens and well in my 20s, I would occasionally pass a rainy Sunday afternoon setting it all out again.  My floral garden has travelled far and wide over the past 40+ years, one of the few of my childhood toys to survive.   During our stay here, my parents brought me to the V&A where I remember vividly the dress collection (who knew?).  So it seems wonderfully appropriate, given the path of my childhood and my career, to offer the floral garden to Bethnal Green Museum.
